  <span id="freeText14259086127958500972" style="display:none">Absolutely loved everything about the virus, T'Rain, and the hackers. Really wish the book would have focused more on that than <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[on the terrorist plot <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. With that, my attention was definitely held - but mostly because I wanted to see the conclusion of the story.<br /><br />One thing that did impress me, though, was the care that was put into ensuring the characters (good and bad ones) made logical decisions. None of Stephenson's characters here are stupid, and it was satisfying to come up with, say, things the antagonists might overlook, only to have them take those things into consideration a few paragraphs later and deal with them.</span>
