    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_221408427" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/221408427" />
    <a title="Moira" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5199637-moira"><img alt="Moira" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1417139162p2/5199637.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/221408427?book_show_action=true">Oct 10, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Moira" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Moira" href="/user/show/5199637-moira">Moira</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer221408427" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7109712868765451719">OK, look. I routinely go into small bookshops and badger clerks to recommend a giant, sprawling, poly-thematic novel, ideally one that takes place in multiple far-flung locales and features kick-ass women. Which is to say, I have read all of Neal Stephenson&apos;s novels, most of them two and three times over. I am a big fan, and just like any partisan, I am somewhat unsuited to anything aside from gushing or howling. <br/><br/>But honestly, I can&apos;t do either. REAMDE a good, long, and involving read. It fails </span>
  <span id="freeText7109712868765451719" style="display:none">OK, look. I routinely go into small bookshops and badger clerks to recommend a giant, sprawling, poly-thematic novel, ideally one that takes place in multiple far-flung locales and features kick-ass women. Which is to say, I have read all of Neal Stephenson's novels, most of them two and three times over. I am a big fan, and just like any partisan, I am somewhat unsuited to anything aside from gushing or howling. <br /><br />But honestly, I can't do either. REAMDE a good, long, and involving read. It fails in some classically Stephensonian ways, chiefly a hurried coda and some tired sexual politics, but it succeeds with a cracking good adventure that's larded with fascinating details on geology, guns, chinese tribal groups, fishing boat typology, internet security, gangster mores, international flight patterns, religious extremism of various stripes, and post-Soviet Hungarian economic failures. <br /><br />I wanted to lose myself in a big old adventure novel and I did. I got an info-dump in the form of a novel, and it was exactly what I wanted. But Reamde is no Baroque Cycle. <br /><br />In fact, let me do what, as a big fan, I am uniquely qualified to do.<br /><br />In descending order of Awesomeness:<br />1: The Baroque Cycle<br />2: Cryptonomicon<br />3: The Diamond Age<br />4: REAMDE<br />5: Snow Crash<br />6: Anathem<br />7: Zodiac </span>
  <a data-text-id="7109712868765451719" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


